# make a dictionary to convert values
movies_bool = {"Star Wars: Episode I  The Phantom Menace": True,
               "Star Wars: Episode II  Attack of the Clones": True,
               "Star Wars: Episode III  Revenge of the Sith": True,
               "Star Wars: Episode IV  A New Hope": True,
               "Star Wars: Episode V The Empire Strikes Back": True,
               "Star Wars: Episode VI Return of the Jedi": True,
               np.nan: False}

# convert values in column to boolean
for c in star_wars.columns[3:9]:
    star_wars[c] = star_wars[c].map(movies_bool)

# make a dictionary of column names to change
col_name = {"Which of the following Star Wars films have you seen? Please select all that apply.": "seen_1",
            "Unnamed: 4": "seen_2",
            "Unnamed: 5": "seen_3",
            "Unnamed: 6": "seen_4",
            "Unnamed: 7": "seen_5",
            "Unnamed: 8": "seen_6"}

# rename column names
star_wars = star_wars.rename(col_name, axis =1)

We computed the mean ranking of every Star Wars movie and found Episode V: Empire Strikes Back to be the best movie in the Star Wars franchise so far. As the result of he first plot is not very intuitive, we invert the ranking in a way that 6 would be the best movie and 1 would be the worst movie. We also calculated the percentages of voters who voted Episode V as the best Star Wars movie and we found that 35% of the respondents voted for Episode V.

We segmented the data based on the the question on Which character shot first? and we found that all three groups agreed that Episode V: Empire Strikes Back is the best movie in the Star Wars franchise and they also agreed that the worst movie in the Star Wars franchise is Episode III: Revenge of the Sith.

Those who understood the question disagree on which is the second best movie. Those who answered Han shot first voted Episode IV as the second best movie and those who answered Greedo voted Episode VI as the second best movie. Aside of the 2nd best movie and the 3rd best movie, both groups agreed on the order of the other movies.

Those who do not understand the question voted the other movies differently compared to the two groups. The order are as the following:

Rank Han shot first Greedo shot first I don't understand the question
Best Ep. V Ep. V Ep. V
2nd Best Ep. IV Ep. VI Ep. I
3rd Best Ep. VI Ep. IV Ep. VI
4th Best Ep. I Ep. I Ep. II
5th Best Ep. II Ep. II Ep. IV
Worst Ep. III Ep. III Ep. III

We included the previous table we made here for quick comparison.

Rank Fans Non-fans
Best Ep. V Ep. V
2nd Best Ep. VI Ep. I
3rd Best Ep. IV Ep. VI
4th Best Ep. I Ep. II
5th Best Ep. II Ep. IV
Worst Ep. III Ep. III

It is interesting that the order of the movies from those who answered Han shot first is different than the order of the movies according to results from those who claimed to be Star Wars fans. It is probably due to the fact that fans who answered Han shot first are outnumbered by fans who are new to the fandom and thus, not being able to understand the question and fans who answered Greedo shot first.

We cleaned columns 15 to 19 and assign points based on the response by the respondents. The assign points are as the following:

  • Very favorably: 2 points
  • Somewhat favorably: 1 point
  • Neither favorably nor unfavorably (neutral): 0
  • Somewhat unfavorably: -1 point
  • Unfamiliar (N/A): 0 point
  • Very unfavorably: -2 points

Based on the points, we could check how favorable the characters are by the points given. From our plot, we found Han Solo to be the most likeable character in the Star Wars franchise and we also found Jar Jar Binks to be the least likeable Star Wars character.

Conclusion¶

In this project, we analyzed the survey results on Star Wars movies by FiveThirtyEight.

We spend most of our analysis on checking the rankings of the movies by different groups such as fans and non-fans. From the rankings, we found Episode V: Empire Strikes Back to be the best Star Wars movie and Episode III: Revenge of the Sith to be the worst Star Wars movie.

552 out of 1186 respondents claimed to be a Star Wars fan. However, we were quite surprised to find that 14 fans haven't watched Episode IV. We were expecting Star Wars fans to have watched all 6 movies or at least the original trilogy (Episode IV, V & VI), so it is weird for us to find fans who haven't watch those movies.

If we are redoing the analysis, we probably would split the respondents to those who have watched all 6 movies with those who haven't watched all 6 movies.
